<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1602,2029]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,416,1782,1807]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Specific diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body length 
<number box="[568,667,1783,1807]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" value="625.0" valueMax="650.0" valueMin="600.0">600–650</number>
µm (two specimens measured)—much larger than the 
<typeStatus box="[1289,1337,1784,1808]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">type</typeStatus>
material from Tatra Mountains. Small black eyes present. The trumpet-shaped buccal tube (
<figureCitation box="[1074,1151,1818,1842]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,260,1936,1961]" captionTargetBox="[243,1344,159,1928]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[243,1345,159,1929]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bertolanius weglarskae (LM). A: habitus (scale bar 200 µm). B: bucco-pharyngeal apparatus in ventro-lateral view. C: claws on leg I – II. D: buccal tube and pharynx, ventral view. E: egg (B – E scale bars 50 µm). Polyvinyl lactophenol preparation." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277619/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
Figs. 
<number box="[1137,1151,1818,1842]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
B and D) rather short and wide (
<number box="[221,250,1857,1881]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" value="63.0">63</number>
µm long and 
<number box="[408,436,1857,1881]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" value="15.0">15</number>
µm wide, in animal of 
<number box="[701,743,1857,1881]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" value="650.0">650</number>
µm). Buccal cavity with a broad band (
<number box="[1192,1207,1857,1881]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" value="2.0">2</number>
nd band) of 
<number box="[1332,1374,1857,1881]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" value="5.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="5.0">5–6</number>
rows of infrabuccal teeth (mucrones or rounded teeth) and a single row (
<number box="[894,908,1896,1920]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" value="3.0">3</number>
rd band) of infrabuccal teeth or ridges (infrabuccal baffles or transverse ridges). First band of infrabuccal teeth, absent. Large triangular apophyses in the pharyngeal bulb (
<figureCitation box="[280,363,1968,1992]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,260,1936,1961]" captionTargetBox="[243,1344,159,1928]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[243,1345,159,1929]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bertolanius weglarskae (LM). A: habitus (scale bar 200 µm). B: bucco-pharyngeal apparatus in ventro-lateral view. C: claws on leg I – II. D: buccal tube and pharynx, ventral view. E: egg (B – E scale bars 50 µm). Polyvinyl lactophenol preparation." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277619/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
Figs. 
<number box="[349,363,1968,1992]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
B and D). Three macroplacoids present, first and second joined, total length 
<number box="[1285,1313,1968,1992]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" value="25.0">25</number>
µm, third macroplacoid 
<number box="[310,338,2004,2028]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" value="13.0">13</number>
µm long. Microplacoid absent (
<figureCitation box="[698,776,2004,2028]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,260,1936,1961]" captionTargetBox="[243,1344,159,1928]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[243,1345,159,1929]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bertolanius weglarskae (LM). A: habitus (scale bar 200 µm). B: bucco-pharyngeal apparatus in ventro-lateral view. C: claws on leg I – II. D: buccal tube and pharynx, ventral view. E: egg (B – E scale bars 50 µm). Polyvinyl lactophenol preparation." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277619/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
Figs. 
<number box="[762,776,2004,2028]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
B and D). Claws of the 
<taxonomicName box="[1041,1201,2004,2028]" class="Eutardigrada" family="Eohypsibiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Parachela" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="family">Eohypsibiidae</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus box="[1208,1256,2005,2029]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">type</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation box="[1271,1339,2004,2028]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,260,1936,1961]" captionTargetBox="[243,1344,159,1928]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[243,1345,159,1929]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bertolanius weglarskae (LM). A: habitus (scale bar 200 µm). B: bucco-pharyngeal apparatus in ventro-lateral view. C: claws on leg I – II. D: buccal tube and pharynx, ventral view. E: egg (B – E scale bars 50 µm). Polyvinyl lactophenol preparation." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277619/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
Fig. 
<number box="[1324,1339,2004,2028]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
C).
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277619/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="43" targetBox="[243,1344,159,1928]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1936,2032]" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,289,1936,1961]" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">FIGURE 2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[296,563,1936,1960]" class="Eutardigrada" family="Eohypsibiidae" genus="Bertolanius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Parachela" pageId="4" pageNumber="43" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="species" species="weglarskae">
<emphasis box="[296,563,1936,1960]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">Bertolanius weglarskae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(LM). A: habitus (scale bar 200 µm). B: bucco-pharyngeal apparatus in ventro-lateral view. C: claws on leg I–II. D: buccal tube and pharynx, ventral view. E: egg (B–E scale bars 50 µm). Polyvinyl lactophenol preparation.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,463]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">
Lunules at the base of all claws, two cuticular bars present (
<figureCitation box="[833,900,151,175]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,260,1936,1961]" captionTargetBox="[243,1344,159,1928]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[243,1345,159,1929]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bertolanius weglarskae (LM). A: habitus (scale bar 200 µm). B: bucco-pharyngeal apparatus in ventro-lateral view. C: claws on leg I – II. D: buccal tube and pharynx, ventral view. E: egg (B – E scale bars 50 µm). Polyvinyl lactophenol preparation." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277619/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">
Fig. 
<number box="[886,900,151,175]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
C) beneath the claws of legs I-III, an accessory cuticular bar close to the internal claws of legs II and III. Yellow eggs laid free, range in diameter from 
<number box="[1307,1391,187,211]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" value="106.5" valueMax="138.0" valueMin="75.0">75–138</number>
µm without the projections (
<figureCitation box="[429,498,223,247]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,260,1936,1961]" captionTargetBox="[243,1344,159,1928]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[243,1345,159,1929]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bertolanius weglarskae (LM). A: habitus (scale bar 200 µm). B: bucco-pharyngeal apparatus in ventro-lateral view. C: claws on leg I – II. D: buccal tube and pharynx, ventral view. E: egg (B – E scale bars 50 µm). Polyvinyl lactophenol preparation." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277619/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">
Fig. 
<number box="[483,498,223,247]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
E). The projections are enveloped in a hyaline layer, of pentamer appearance, producing on the surface a regular reticular network, with wide mesh.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="44" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,463]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,313,295,319]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">Remarks.</emphasis>
Except for the large size, the Faroese specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[925,1086,295,319]" class="Eutardigrada" family="Eohypsibiidae" genus="Bertolanius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Parachela" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="species" species="weglarskae">
<emphasis box="[925,1086,295,319]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">B. weglarskae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fit the description of the 
<typeStatus box="[1387,1435,296,320]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">type</typeStatus>
material from 
<collectingCountry box="[317,395,330,354]" name="Poland" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">Poland</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dastych" box="[412,572,330,354]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" refString="Dastych, H. (1972) Isohypsibius weglarskae sp. n. a new species of Tardigrada from Poland. Bulletin de l'Academie Polonaise des Sciences. Serie des Sciences Biologiques, Cl. II. Vol. XX, No. 11, pp. 761 - 765." type="book chapter" year="1972">
Dastych 
<number box="[515,572,330,354]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" value="1972.0">1972</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) and the re-description of the species based on the Greenlandic specimens (
<bibRefCitation author="Hansen" box="[158,459,367,391]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" refString="Hansen, J. G. &amp; Katholm, A. K. (2002) A study of the genus Amphibolus from Disko Island with special attention on the life cycle of Amphibolus nebulosus (Eutardigrada: Eohypsibiidae). In: Arctic Biology Field Course, Qeqertarsuaq 2002, pp. 129 - 163. Zoological Museum, University of Copenhagen. ISBN: 87 - 87519 - 58 - 5." type="journal article" year="2002">
Hansen &amp; Katholm 
<number box="[398,459,367,391]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Brown cysts were found in “Við Áir” homothermic spring and on the summit of Vaðhorn. The species has been collected from 
<collectingCountry box="[697,779,402,426]" name="Iceland" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">Iceland</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Marley" box="[797,1072,402,426]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" refString="Marley, N. J. &amp; Wright, D. E. (1996) Amphibolus weglarskae (Dastych), a new addition to the Tardigrada of Iceland with an updated checklist of Icelandic species (Eohypsibiidae, Eutardigrada). Quekett Journal of Microscopy, 37, 541 - 545." type="journal article" year="1996">
Marley &amp; Wright 
<number box="[1012,1072,402,426]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" value="1996.0">1996</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[1094,1194,402,426]" name="Svalbard and Jan Mayen" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">Svalbard</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Coulson" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" refString="Coulson, S. J. &amp; Refseth, D. (2004) The terrestrial and freshwater invertebrate fauna of Svalbard (and Jan Mayen), pp 57 - 122. In: Strom, H. and Goldman, H. (eds), A catalogue of the terrestrial and marine animals. Skrifter 201, Norwegian Polar Institute, Troms." type="journal article" year="2004">
Coulson &amp; Refseth 
<number box="[151,209,439,463]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) and has a mainly northern Holarctic distribution (McInnes, pers. comm.).
</paragraph>
